{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Hello! My name is Golan Levin."},{"time":3000,"text":"I'm an artist and an engineer,"},{"time":5000,"text":"which is, increasingly, a more common kind of hybrid."},{"time":7000,"text":"But I still fall into this weird crack"},{"time":10000,"text":"where people don't seem to understand me."},{"time":12000,"text":"And I was looking around and I found this wonderful picture."},{"time":16000,"text":"It's a letter from \"Artforum\" in 1967"},{"time":19000,"text":"saying \"We can't imagine ever doing a special issue"},{"time":22000,"text":"on electronics or computers in art.\" And they still haven't."},{"time":25000,"text":"And lest you think that you all, as the digerati, are more enlightened,"},{"time":30000,"text":"I went to the Apple iPhone app store the other day."},{"time":33000,"text":"Where's art? I got productivity. I got sports."},{"time":37000,"text":"And somehow the idea that one would want to make art for the iPhone,"},{"time":41000,"text":"which my friends and I are doing now,"},{"time":43000,"text":"is still not reflected in our understanding"},{"time":46000,"text":"of what computers are for."}]},{"cues":[{"time":48000,"text":"So, from both directions, there is kind of, I think, a lack of understanding"},{"time":50000,"text":"about what it could mean to be an artist who uses the materials"},{"time":52000,"text":"of his own day, or her own day,"},{"time":54000,"text":"which I think artists are obliged to do,"},{"time":56000,"text":"is to really explore the expressive potential of the new tools that we have."},{"time":60000,"text":"In my own case, I'm an artist,"},{"time":62000,"text":"and I'm really interested in"},{"time":64000,"text":"expanding the vocabulary of human action,"},{"time":66000,"text":"and basically empowering people through interactivity."},{"time":69000,"text":"I want people to discover themselves as actors,"},{"time":72000,"text":"as creative actors, by having interactive experiences."}]},{"cues":[{"time":76000,"text":"A lot of my work is about trying to get away from this."},{"time":79000,"text":"This a photograph of the desktop of a student of mine."},{"time":81000,"text":"And when I say desktop, I don't just mean"},{"time":83000,"text":"the actual desk where his mouse has worn away the surface of the desk."},{"time":86000,"text":"If you look carefully, you can even see"},{"time":88000,"text":"a hint of the Apple menu, up here in the upper left,"},{"time":91000,"text":"where the virtual world has literally"},{"time":93000,"text":"punched through to the physical."},{"time":95000,"text":"So this is, as Joy Mountford once said,"},{"time":99000,"text":"\"The mouse is probably the narrowest straw"},{"time":101000,"text":"you could try to suck all of human expression through.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":103000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":106000,"text":"And the thing I'm really trying to do is enabling people to have more rich"},{"time":109000,"text":"kinds of interactive experiences."},{"time":111000,"text":"How can we get away from the mouse and use our full bodies"},{"time":113000,"text":"as a way of exploring aesthetic experiences,"},{"time":116000,"text":"not necessarily utilitarian ones."},{"time":118000,"text":"So I write software. And that's how I do it."},{"time":121000,"text":"And a lot of my experiences"},{"time":123000,"text":"resemble mirrors in some way."},{"time":125000,"text":"Because this is, in some sense, the first way,"},{"time":127000,"text":"that people discover their own potential as actors,"},{"time":129000,"text":"and discover their own agency."},{"time":131000,"text":"By saying \"Who is that person in the mirror? Oh it's actually me.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"And so, to give an example,"},{"time":136000,"text":"this is a project from last year,"},{"time":138000,"text":"which is called the Interstitial Fragment Processor."},{"time":140000,"text":"And it allows people to explore the negative shapes that they create"},{"time":144000,"text":"when they're just going about their everyday business."},{"time":161000,"text":"So as people make shapes with their hands or their heads"},{"time":163000,"text":"and so forth, or with each other,"},{"time":165000,"text":"these shapes literally produce sounds and drop out of thin air --"},{"time":168000,"text":"basically taking what's often this, kind of, unseen space,"},{"time":172000,"text":"or this undetected space, and making it something real,"},{"time":175000,"text":"that people then can appreciate and become creative with."},{"time":178000,"text":"So again, people discover their creative agency in this way."},{"time":181000,"text":"And their own personalities come out"},{"time":183000,"text":"in totally unique ways."}]},{"cues":[{"time":186000,"text":"So in addition to using full-body input,"},{"time":189000,"text":"something that I've explored now, for a while,"},{"time":191000,"text":"has been the use of the voice,"},{"time":193000,"text":"which is an immensely expressive system for us, vocalizing."},{"time":197000,"text":"Song is one of our oldest ways"},{"time":199000,"text":"of making ourselves heard and understood."},{"time":202000,"text":"And I came across this fantastic research by Wolfgang KÃ¶hler,"},{"time":204000,"text":"the so-called father of gestalt psychology, from 1927,"},{"time":208000,"text":"who submitted to an audience like yourselves"},{"time":210000,"text":"the following two shapes."},{"time":212000,"text":"And he said one of them is called Maluma."},{"time":214000,"text":"And one of them is called Taketa. Which is which?"},{"time":216000,"text":"Anyone want to hazard a guess?"},{"time":220000,"text":"Maluma is on top. Yeah. So."},{"time":222000,"text":"As he says here, most people answer without any hesitation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":225000,"text":"So what we're really seeing here is a phenomenon"},{"time":227000,"text":"called phonaesthesia,"},{"time":229000,"text":"which is a kind of synesthesia that all of you have."},{"time":231000,"text":"And so, whereas Dr. Oliver Sacks has talked about"},{"time":233000,"text":"how perhaps one person in a million"},{"time":235000,"text":"actually has true synesthesia,"},{"time":237000,"text":"where they hear colors or taste shapes, and things like this,"},{"time":239000,"text":"phonaesthesia is something we can all experience to some extent."},{"time":241000,"text":"It's about mappings between different perceptual domains,"},{"time":244000,"text":"like hardness, sharpness, brightness and darkness,"},{"time":247000,"text":"and the phonemes that we're able to speak with."}]},{"cues":[{"time":249000,"text":"So 70 years on, there's been some research where"},{"time":251000,"text":"cognitive psychologists have actually sussed out"},{"time":253000,"text":"the extent to which, you know,"},{"time":255000,"text":"L, M and B are more associated with shapes that look like this,"},{"time":259000,"text":"and P, T and K are perhaps more associated with shapes like this."},{"time":263000,"text":"And here we suddenly begin to have a mapping between curvature"},{"time":265000,"text":"that we can exploit numerically,"},{"time":267000,"text":"a relative mapping between curvature and shape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":270000,"text":"So it occurred to me, what happens if we could run these backwards?"},{"time":273000,"text":"And thus was born the project called Remark,"},{"time":275000,"text":"which is a collaboration with Zachary Lieberman"},{"time":277000,"text":"and the Ars Electronica Futurelab."},{"time":279000,"text":"And this is an interactive installation which presents"},{"time":281000,"text":"the fiction that speech casts visible shadows."},{"time":283000,"text":"So the idea is you step into a kind of a magic light."},{"time":286000,"text":"And as you do, you see the shadows of your own speech."},{"time":289000,"text":"And they sort of fly away, out of your head."},{"time":291000,"text":"If a computer speech recognition system"},{"time":294000,"text":"is able to recognize what you're saying, then it spells it out."},{"time":298000,"text":"And if it isn't then it produces a shape which is very phonaesthetically"},{"time":300000,"text":"tightly coupled to the sounds you made."},{"time":302000,"text":"So let's bring up a video of that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":351000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":353000,"text":"Thanks. So. And this project here,"},{"time":356000,"text":"I was working with the great abstract vocalist, Jaap Blonk."},{"time":359000,"text":"And he is a world expert in performing \"The Ursonate,\""},{"time":362000,"text":"which is a half-an-hour nonsense poem"},{"time":364000,"text":"by Kurt Schwitters, written in the 1920s,"},{"time":366000,"text":"which is half an hour of very highly patterned nonsense."},{"time":370000,"text":"And it's almost impossible to perform."},{"time":372000,"text":"But Jaap is one of the world experts in performing it."},{"time":375000,"text":"And in this project we've developed"},{"time":377000,"text":"a form of intelligent real-time subtitles."},{"time":380000,"text":"So these are our live subtitles,"},{"time":383000,"text":"that are being produced by a computer that knows the text of \"The Ursonate\" --"},{"time":386000,"text":"fortunately Jaap does too, very well --"},{"time":389000,"text":"and it is delivering that text at the same time as Jaap is."},{"time":401000,"text":"So all the text you're going to see"},{"time":403000,"text":"is real-time generated by the computer,"},{"time":405000,"text":"visualizing what he's doing with his voice."},{"time":478000,"text":"Here you can see the set-up where there is a screen with the subtitles behind him."},{"time":502000,"text":"Okay. So ..."},{"time":504000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":509000,"text":"The full videos are online if you are interested."}]},{"cues":[{"time":511000,"text":"I got a split reaction to that during the live performance,"},{"time":513000,"text":"because there is some people who understand"},{"time":515000,"text":"live subtitles are a kind of an oxymoron,"},{"time":517000,"text":"because usually there is someone making them afterwards."},{"time":520000,"text":"And then a bunch of people who were like, \"What's the big deal?"},{"time":523000,"text":"I see subtitles all the time on television.\""},{"time":525000,"text":"You know? They don't imagine the person in the booth, typing it all."}]},{"cues":[{"time":528000,"text":"So in addition to the full body, and in addition to the voice,"},{"time":531000,"text":"another thing that I've been really interested in,"},{"time":533000,"text":"most recently, is the use of the eyes,"},{"time":535000,"text":"or the gaze, in terms of how people relate to each other."},{"time":539000,"text":"It's a really profound amount of nonverbal information"},{"time":541000,"text":"that's communicated with the eyes."},{"time":543000,"text":"And it's one of the most interesting technical challenges"},{"time":545000,"text":"that's very currently active in the computer sciences:"},{"time":547000,"text":"being able to have a camera that can understand,"},{"time":549000,"text":"from a fairly big distance away,"},{"time":551000,"text":"how these little tiny balls are actually pointing in one way or another"},{"time":554000,"text":"to reveal what you're interested in,"},{"time":556000,"text":"and where your attention is directed."},{"time":558000,"text":"So there is a lot of emotional communication that happens there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":561000,"text":"And so I've been beginning, with a variety of different projects,"},{"time":565000,"text":"to understand how people can relate to machines with their eyes."},{"time":568000,"text":"And basically to ask the questions:"},{"time":571000,"text":"What if art was aware that we were looking at it?"},{"time":576000,"text":"How could it respond, in a way,"},{"time":578000,"text":"to acknowledge or subvert the fact that we're looking at it?"},{"time":581000,"text":"And what could it do if it could look back at us?"},{"time":584000,"text":"And so those are the questions that are happening in the next projects."}]},{"cues":[{"time":586000,"text":"In the first one which I'm going to show you, called Eyecode,"},{"time":589000,"text":"it's a piece of interactive software"},{"time":591000,"text":"in which, if we read this little circle,"},{"time":593000,"text":"\"the trace left by the looking of the previous observer"},{"time":596000,"text":"looks at the trace left by the looking of previous observer.\""},{"time":599000,"text":"The idea is that it's an image wholly constructed"},{"time":601000,"text":"from its own history of being viewed"},{"time":603000,"text":"by different people in an installation."},{"time":605000,"text":"So let me just switch over so we can do the live demo."},{"time":610000,"text":"So let's run this and see if it works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":614000,"text":"Okay. Ah, there is lots of nice bright video."},{"time":617000,"text":"There is just a little test screen that shows that it's working."},{"time":619000,"text":"And what I'm just going to do is -- I'm going to hide that."},{"time":621000,"text":"And you can see here that what it's doing"},{"time":623000,"text":"is it's recording my eyes every time I blink."},{"time":632000,"text":"Hello? And I can ... hello ... okay."},{"time":636000,"text":"And no matter where I am, what's really going on here"},{"time":638000,"text":"is that it's an eye-tracking system that tries to locate my eyes."},{"time":641000,"text":"And if I get really far away I'm blurry."},{"time":643000,"text":"You know, you're going to have these kind of blurry spots like this"},{"time":645000,"text":"that maybe only resemble eyes in a very very abstract way."},{"time":648000,"text":"But if I come up really close and stare directly at the camera"},{"time":651000,"text":"on this laptop then you'll see these nice crisp eyes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":653000,"text":"You can think of it as a way of, sort of, typing, with your eyes."},{"time":657000,"text":"And what you're typing are recordings of your eyes"},{"time":659000,"text":"as you're looking at other peoples' eyes."},{"time":661000,"text":"So each person is looking at the looking"},{"time":664000,"text":"of everyone else before them."},{"time":666000,"text":"And this exists in larger installations"},{"time":668000,"text":"where there are thousands and thousands of eyes"},{"time":670000,"text":"that people could be staring at,"},{"time":672000,"text":"as you see who's looking at the people looking"},{"time":674000,"text":"at the people looking before them."},{"time":676000,"text":"So I'll just add a couple more. Blink. Blink."},{"time":679000,"text":"And you can see, just once again, how it's sort of finding my eyes"},{"time":682000,"text":"and doing its best to estimate when it's blinking."},{"time":685000,"text":"Alright. Let's leave that."},{"time":687000,"text":"So that's this kind of recursive observation system."},{"time":690000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":692000,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":694000,"text":"The last couple pieces I'm going to show"},{"time":696000,"text":"are basically in the new realm of robotics -- for me, new for me."},{"time":698000,"text":"It's called Opto-Isolator."},{"time":700000,"text":"And I'm going to show a video of the older version of it,"},{"time":703000,"text":"which is just a minute long. Okay."},{"time":714000,"text":"In this case, the Opto-Isolator is blinking"},{"time":716000,"text":"in response to one's own blinks."},{"time":718000,"text":"So it blinks one second after you do."},{"time":721000,"text":"This is a device which is intended to reduce"},{"time":724000,"text":"the phenomenon of gaze down to the simplest possible materials."},{"time":727000,"text":"Just one eye,"},{"time":729000,"text":"looking at you, and eliminating everything else about a face,"},{"time":731000,"text":"but just to consider gaze in an isolated way"},{"time":734000,"text":"as a kind of, as an element."},{"time":737000,"text":"And at the same time, it attempts to engage in what you might call"},{"time":740000,"text":"familiar psycho-social gaze behaviors."},{"time":742000,"text":"Like looking away if you look at it too long"},{"time":744000,"text":"because it gets shy,"},{"time":746000,"text":"or things like that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":749000,"text":"Okay. So the last project I'm going to show"},{"time":752000,"text":"is this new one called Snout."},{"time":755000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":757000,"text":"It's an eight-foot snout,"},{"time":759000,"text":"with a googly eye."},{"time":761000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":762000,"text":"And inside it's got an 800-pound robot arm"},{"time":765000,"text":"that I borrowed,"},{"time":767000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":768000,"text":"from a friend."},{"time":770000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":771000,"text":"It helps to have good friends."},{"time":773000,"text":"I'm at Carnegie Mellon; we've got a great Robotics Institute there."},{"time":776000,"text":"I'd like to show you thing called Snout, which is --"},{"time":778000,"text":"The idea behind this project is to"},{"time":780000,"text":"make a robot that appears as if it's continually surprised to see you."},{"time":784000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":788000,"text":"The idea is that basically --"},{"time":790000,"text":"if it's constantly like \"Huh? ... Huh?\""},{"time":792000,"text":"That's why its other name is Doubletaker, Taker of Doubles."},{"time":796000,"text":"It's always kind of doing a double take: \"What?\""},{"time":798000,"text":"And the idea is basically, can it look at you"},{"time":800000,"text":"and make you feel as if like,"},{"time":802000,"text":"\"What? Is it my shoes?\""},{"time":804000,"text":"\"Got something on my hair?\" Here we go. Alright."}]},{"cues":[{"time":838000,"text":"Checking him out ..."},{"time":848000,"text":"For you nerds, here's a little behind-the-scenes."},{"time":850000,"text":"It's got a computer vision system,"},{"time":852000,"text":"and it tries to look at the people who are moving around the most."},{"time":867000,"text":"Those are its targets."},{"time":870000,"text":"Up there is the skeleton,"},{"time":872000,"text":"which is actually what it's trying to do."},{"time":882000,"text":"It's really about trying to create a novel body language for a new creature."},{"time":885000,"text":"Hollywood does this all the time, of course."},{"time":887000,"text":"But also have the body language communicate something"},{"time":889000,"text":"to the person who is looking at it."},{"time":891000,"text":"This language is communicating that it is surprised to see you,"},{"time":893000,"text":"and it's interested in looking at you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":896000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":898000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":907000,"text":"Thank you very much. That's all I've got for today."},{"time":909000,"text":"And I'm really happy to be here. Thank you so much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":912000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}